WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.240
Most technology is built top-down, actively penalizing vulnerable groups, but a framework

00:00:06.240 --> 00:00:09.760
called Design Justice flips this completely.

00:00:09.760 --> 00:00:14.800
It asks, what happens when marginalized people get total control of the code?

00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:19.200
Take this group of black high school students, tasked with designing an app to navigate daily

00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:20.360
threats.

00:00:20.360 --> 00:00:25.160
Standard tech usually views these students as data to be extracted, or problems to be

00:00:25.160 --> 00:00:30.200
surveilled, and it's nearly impossible to build for true liberation using tools designed

00:00:30.200 --> 00:00:32.640
to uphold existing power.

00:00:32.640 --> 00:00:34.720
Design Justice shifts the power.

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:39.900
The app's features are dictated entirely by the lived experience of the most affected.

00:00:39.900 --> 00:00:44.680
When the students built their interface, they started with a radar-style navigation system.

00:00:44.680 --> 00:00:49.000
This lets users map and avoid racially hostile encounters in real time.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:53.240
And if a confrontation happens, they didn't just add a standard 911 button.

00:00:53.240 --> 00:00:58.440
Instead, victims report harassment to community partners, prioritizing safety over state-led

00:00:58.440 --> 00:01:00.000
police surveillance.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.600
The app even includes a feature to anonymously schedule therapy sessions for anxiety.

00:01:04.600 --> 00:01:08.520
By designing a system that centers healing rather than punishment, they employed an

00:01:08.520 --> 00:01:10.720
abolitionist approach to computing.

00:01:10.720 --> 00:01:14.960
By putting their own lived experience at the very center of the design process, these

00:01:14.960 --> 00:01:19.720
students used code to build a practical blueprint for a world that protects instead of police's.
